cs.SI, cs.SOC, cs.IR, cs.DB, cs.CL 

This paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of Social and Information Retrieval (cs.SI) as it proposes an ontology schema for semantification provision of Twitter social analytics. It also involves measuring the influence of Twitter accounts, which falls under the category of social analytics. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of SPARQL endpoint for semantic queries, which is a common technique used in information retrieval. 

The paper could also belong to the sub-category of Social Computing (cs.SOC) as it deals with analyzing social activity and interaction over Twittersphere. 

The sub-category of Information Retrieval (cs.IR) is also likely as the paper involves providing a service that measures the influence of Twitter accounts and allows users to perform advanced semantic queries. 

The sub-category of Databases (cs.DB) is relevant as the paper involves RDFizing Twitter entities and deploying an ontology schema over a publicly available service. 

Finally, the sub-category of Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) is also possible as the paper deals with analyzing Twitter entities such as mentions, replies, hashtags, and photos, which are all related to natural language processing.
